{{Orphan|date=March 2018}} '''Azad Peroz''', known in Arabic sources as '''Azad Firuz''', was a [[Sasanian]] nobleman who served as the governor of [[Eastern Arabia|Bahrain]] during the reign of [[Khosrow II]] (590-628). The Arabs gave him the nickname of "''Mukabir''" (the mutilating), because he cut the hands and feet of other people.<ref name="iranicaonline.org">[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/azad-firuz-governor-of-bahrain ''ĀZĀD FĪRŪZ'', (A. Tafażżolī), '''Encyclopaedia Iranica''']</ref> He was the son of a man named Gushnasp.
According to a tradition, a caravan of gifts sent by the Sasanian governor [[Vahriz]] to Khosrow II was attacked by the Banu Yarbu tribe. Khosrow II then ordered the governor of Bahrain, Azad Peroz, to punish the tribe. To do that, Azad Peroz invited the Banu Yarbu tribe to the Moshakkar Castle in [[Al Hajar Mountains|Hajar]], where he killed everyone except the boys, who were sent in captivity to [[Estakhr]].
During the [[Spread of Islam|rise of Islam]], Azad Peroz converted to the religion and later died during the reign of [[Caliph]] [[Umar]].<ref name="iranicaonline.org"/>
