{{Infobox ancient site | name = Musalla complex | native_name = | native_name_lang = | alternate_name = Musallah complex, Gauhar Shad Musallah | image = Herat Remains of Musallah complex.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Remains of Musalla Complex seen on 2005. | map = | map_type = Afghanistan | map_alt = | map_caption = Location in Afghanistan | map_size = 220 | altitude_m = | altitude_ref = | relief = | coordinates = {{Coord|34.359284|N|62.18608|E|region:IN-DL_type:landmark_scale:50|display=title}} | gbgridref = | map_dot_label = Herat | location = [[Herat]], [[Afghanistan]] | region = [[Herat Province]] | type = [[Islamic]] religious complex | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | volume = | diameter = | circumference = | height = 55 m (180 ft) minarets | builder = [[Goharshad Begum|Queen Goharshad]] of [[Timurid Empire]] of Herāt. | material = | built = 1417 | abandoned = 1885 | epochs = <!-- actually displays as "Periods" --> | cultures = [[Islamic]] | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = 1885 destruction by British. | discovered = | excavations = | archaeologists = | condition = Ruined | ownership = | management = | public_access = Yes | other_designation = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | architectural_styles = [[Timurid architecture|Timurid]] | architectural_details = Timurid Mosque, Shah Rukh [[madressa]], mausoleums, 20 minarets, | notes = }}
'''Musalla complex''' (also called Musallah Complex, Musalla of Gawhar Shad) is a large former Islamic religious complex located in Herat city in western Afghanistan. The 15th century complex is in ruins today. The complex ruins consist of the five huge 55 metre (180 feet) [[Musalla Minarets of Herat|Musallah Minarets of Herat]], mausoleums of Mir Ali Sher Navai, Hussein Baiqara and the ruins of a large [[mosque]] and Islamic [[madrasa]] school buildings. The complex was begun in 1417 by Queen [[Goharshad Begum]], the wife of Timurid ruler [[Shah Rukh]] who established Herat as the capital of the [[Timurid Empire]].<ref>[[ArchNet]], Masjid-i Jami'-i Gawhar Shad, Herat, Afghanistan, https://archnet.org/sites/3935/media_contents/40280</ref>
== History == It is thought that a madrasa was built in 1417 and a mosque was then built in 1426.<ref>[[ArchNet]], Masjid-i Jami'-i Gawhar Shad, Herat, Afghanistan, https://archnet.org/sites/3935/media_contents/40280</ref> Sultan Husain's Madrasa was most likely built around 1493 (898 A.H.). The site contains examples of Timurid architecture although it has been heavily damaged, first by artillery fire in 1863, then during the [[Panjdeh incident]] of 1885 when most of the ruins were razed in an attempt to prevent its use as a base by the invading Russian army. Finally, an earthquake in 1932 destroyed two of the mosque's four minarets.<ref>[[ArchNet]], Masjid-i Jami'-i Gawhar Shad, Herat, Afghanistan, https://archnet.org/sites/3935/media_contents/40280</ref>
The site rose to the attention of Europeans when it was visited and photographed in the 1930s by the travel writers [[Robert Byron]] and [[Annemarie Schwarzenbach]]. Byron's book, [[The Road to Oxiana]] mentions the minarets and discusses Timurid history.
== Preservation == Some emergency preservation work was carried out at the site in 2001 which included building protective walls around the Gawhar Shad Mausoleum and Sultan Husain Madrasa, repairing the remaining minaret of Gawhar Shad's Madrasa, and replanting the mausoleum garden.<ref>[[ArchNet]], Masjid-i Jami'-i Gawhar Shad, Herat, Afghanistan, https://archnet.org/sites/3935/media_contents/40280</ref><ref>https://archnet.org/sites/3935/media_contents/40280</ref><ref>http://www.touristspots.org/mousallah-complex-in-herat-afghanistan/</ref><ref>http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1059997.html</ref><ref>http://www.adventuretravelphotos.com/?Action=_VC&id=77029</ref> ==Gallery== <gallery mode="packed"> File:CH-NB - Afghanistan, Herat- Musalla-Komplex2 - Annemarie Schwarzenbach - SLA-Schwarzenbach-A-5-19-162 (cropped).jpg|Photo by Annemarie Schwarzenbach, 1939 File:CH-NB - Afghanistan, Herat- Musalla-Komplex - Annemarie Schwarzenbach - SLA-Schwarzenbach-A-5-19-164.jpg|Photo by Annemarie Schwarzenbach, 1939 File:2009 Musalla Complex Herat Afghanistan 4112214896.jpg|2009 File:Herat Remains of Musallah complex.jpg|Traffic passing near the site File:Gawhar shad-1417-2.jpg| Ruined Gawhar shad mausoleum. File:CH-NB - Afghanistan, Herat- Musalla-Komplex - Annemarie Schwarzenbach - SLA-Schwarzenbach-A-5-19-173 (cropped2).jpg|Remaining minarets in 1939-40. File:2009 Musalla Complex Herat Afghanistan 4112214558.jpg| Musoleum in 2009. File:2009 Herat Afghanistan 4072962142.jpg|Vegetable Stands near the ruins in 2009. File:2009 Musalla Complex Herat Afghanistan 4112214218.jpg| A minaret in 2009. File:Musalla Complex in 2009.jpg| New replanted trees in complex garden in 2009. File:Gawharshad Musalla D60.jpg|Minaret in 1962. File:Herat 6918a.jpg| Minaret in 1969. File:Minarety - Herat - 001467s.jpg|The site in 1975. File:Herat 6961a.jpg|Herat skyline with Musallah minarets in 1969. File:2009 view Herat Afghanistan 4072191719.jpg|Herat skyline with Musallah minarets in 2009. </gal