[[File:The Temple of Lord Guan in Chaoyang 27 2015-09.JPG|thumb|Temple of [[Guan Yu|Guandi]] in [[Chaoyang, Liaoning|Chaoyang]], [[Liaoning]]. The martial character of Guandi make him appealing not only for Han Chinese by also for Manchus.{{sfnb|Elliott|2001|p=239}}]]
{{Chinese folk religion}}
'''Northeast China folk religion'''{{refn|group=note|The general description in [[Chinese language]] is 東北民間宗教 ''Dōngběi mínjiān zōngjiào'' or 東北民間信仰 ''Dōngběi mínjiān xìnyǎng''.}} is the variety of [[Chinese folk religion]] of [[northeast China]], characterised by distinctive cults original to [[Hebei]] and [[Shandong]], transplanted and adapted by the [[Han Chinese]] settlers of [[Liaoning]], [[Jilin]] and [[Heilongjiang]] (the three provinces comprising [[Manchuria]]) since the [[Qing dynasty]].{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=19}} It is characterised by terminology, deities and practices that are different from those of central and southern Chinese folk religion. Many of these patterns derive from the interaction of Han religion with [[Manchu shamanism]].{{sfnb|Liu|2007}}

Prominence is given to the worship of [[animal worship|zoomorphic deities]], of a "[[totemism|totemic]]" significance.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=1}}{{sfnb|Liu|2007}} In the region the terms ''[[shen (Chinese religion)|shen]]'' 神 ("god") and ''[[xian (Taoism)|xian]]'' 仙 ("immortal being") are synonymous. Figures of ritual specialists or [[shamans]]{{refn|group=note|Shamans are variously called:
* Simply ''dìzǐ'' 弟子, "disciples (of the gods)";{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=1}}
* ''Dàxiān er'' 大仙兒, "children of the great gods";
* ''Tiào dàshén'' 跳大神, "dancers of the great gods".{{sfnb|Liu|2007}}}} perform various [[ritual]] functions for groups of believers and local communities, including ''chūmǎxiān'' (出馬仙 "riding for the immortals"),{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=17}} dances, [[healing]], [[exorcism]], [[divination]], and communication with [[ancestor]]s.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=2}}

==History==
[[File:Roadside shrine in Manchuria.jpg|thumb|A roadside shrine in Manchuria. (1888)]]
The formation of northeast China's folk religion and shamanism can be traced back to the [[Qing dynasty]] (1644-1911), when a large number of [[Han Chinese]] settled in the northeast of China mixing with [[Manchu people|Manchus]].{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=45}} Either in the Qing period, and in the later [[Republic of China (1912-1949)]] and subsequent People's Republic, the worship of zoomorphic deities and the practice of ''chumaxian'' had bad relationship with the governments,{{sfnb|Deng|2014|pp=45-46}} which considered it "feudal superstition" (封建迷信 ''fēngjiàn míxìn''){{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=3}} and banned through different decrees.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|pp=46-49}}

The popular worship of animal gods began to resurface in the 1980s, and soon also the ''chumaxian'' practice was revived.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|pp=50-51}} In the 2010s there have been attempts to protect ''chumaxian'' under the policy of "intangible cultural heritage".{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=52}}

===Japanese scholarship and Shinto similarities===
[[Image:---File---蒙疆神社.JPG|thumb|Shinto shrine in [[Zhangjiakou]], [[Hebei]], [[China]], in the 1950s, when it was already abandoned. The shrine was founded by the Japanese during World War II, and incorporated Mongol Genghis Khan worship.]]
The study of northeast China's folk religion owes much to the scholarly enterprise that the [[Japanese people|Japanese]] conducted on the subject during the period of ''[[Manchukuo]]'' (1932–1945) that they established after they [[Japanese invasion of Manchuria|occupied Manchuria]].{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=53}} Unlike [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese-occupied Korea]] and [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|occupied Taiwan]], Manchuria was conceived as an autonomous nation, not to be assimilated into [[Japan]], but rather to be modeled after the latter's social and religious structure keeping an independent identity.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|pp=56-57}}

Ōmachi Tokuzo (1909-1970), a pupil of Yanagita Kunio (the founder of academic ethnography in Japan), conducted field research on local religion in Manchuria through the war years.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=59}} He later acted as the head of the Society for the Study of Manchurian Customs, producing an impressive body of research on local religion in Manchuria and north China.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=61}} Ōmachi identified the rural village, each with a [[Tudishen]] shrine, as the fundamental unit of northeast China's local religion and of the religious character of the [[Han Chinese]] race.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|pp=62-63}} He also studies local Chinese goddess worship and the great similarity and integration of the Han and the Manchus.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|pp=63-64}} Ōmachi does not appear to have supported the institution of [[Shinto shrines]] in Manchurian villages, which in Korea and Taiwan were intended for the spiritual transformation of the locals into Japanese citizens by their integration into Shinto communities.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=64}}

Another scholar, Tokunaga Takeshi, sought to demonstrate the spiritual unity of Japan, Manchuria and China by highlighting the similarities between ancient religious structures of the three nations:{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=65}}

<blockquote>Japanese ancient shrines are of the ''kannabi'' (popularly known as [[Mt. Fuji]]-style) shape. There are many of these in Manchuria, as well ... [The artifacts] develop from the same agrarian culture and philosophy as Japanese Shinto (''kannagara no michi'') ... Modern [Chinese] matron temples have these elements, as well. Therefore, since the temples were built later, it is thought that matron worship was grafted onto this earlier pattern of belief.<ref>{{citation|last=Okumura|first=Yoshinobu|title=Manshu nyannyan ko|trans-title=Study of Niangniang Temples in Manchuria|location=Shinkyo (Changchun)|year=1940|pages=242–245}}.</ref></blockquote>

Other scholars studied the similarities between local and Japanese shamanisms.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=65}} The ''Manchukuo'' generally promoted a racially centered spiritual revival, that is an [[ethnic religion]] for each of the races inhabiting Manchuria.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=68}} For example, under the suggestions of Ogasawara Shozo that the [[Mongols in China|Mongols]] "need(ed) a new religion, specifically a new god" they promoted the worship of [[Genghis Khan]] that continues today in northern China. The Shinto shrine of Kalgan (now [[Zhangjiakou]], [[Hebei]]) incorporated Genghis Khan worship and was opened to local Mongols.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=69}}

==Characteristics==
[[File:万福鼎.JPG|thumb|"Myriad Prosperities' Cauldron" (万福鼎 ''Wànfú Dǐng''), with the name of the [[Sanxing (deities)|"Prosperity God" or "Fortune God"]] (福星 ''Fúxīng'') inscribed ten thousand times, in [[Jinzhou]], [[Dalian]], Liaoning.]]

===Deities===
{{Main|Wudaxian}}
Besides common Chinese deities such as ''[[Guan Yu|Guāndì]]'' (关帝 "''[[Divus]]'' Guan", the god of war),{{sfnb|Kang|2006|p=49}} people of north China and Manchuria have distinctive [[animal worship|zoomorphic deities]],{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=22}} and the [[Chinese mother goddess worship|worship of clusters of goddesses]] is popular. The gods are ordained in hierarchies, a pattern inherited from the Chinese [[Confucianism|Confucian]] lineage system.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=22}} [[Fox spirit|Fox deities]] have a very important position,{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=21}} with evident parallels in the [[Japan]]ese cult of [[Inari Ōkami]].{{sfnb|Kang|2006|pp=199-200}} Usually at the head of the pantheon are placed the "Great Lord of the Three Foxes" (胡三太爷 ''Húsān Tàiyé'') and the "Great Lady of the Three Foxes" (胡三太奶 ''Húsān Tàinǎi'').{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=75}}

The Five Great Immortals (五大仙 ''Wǔdàxiān'') are deities who reproduce [[cosmology|cosmological]] structures of common [[Chinese theology]]. The cult generally includes: ① ''[[Huxian|Húxiān]]'' (狐仙=胡仙 "Fox Immortal") or ''Húshén'' (狐神 "Fox God"), the most important deity in northeast China;{{sfnb|Kang|2006|pp=45-50}} ② ''Huángxiān'' (黃仙 literally "Yellow Immortal") the Weasel God, who holds the position of the [[Yellow Deity]] of Chinese theology; ③ ''Shéxiān'' (蛇仙 literally "Snake Immortal"), also called ''Liǔxiān'' (柳仙 "Immortal Liu") or ''Mǎngxiān'' (蟒仙 "Python (or Boa) Immortal"), who can represent the [[Dragon God]], [[Fuxi]] and [[Nüwa]]; ④ ''Báixiān'' (白仙 "White Immortal") is the Hedgehog God; and ⑤ ''Hēixiān'' (黑仙 "Black Immortal") who can be the ''Wūyāxiān'' (乌鸦仙 "Crow Immortal") or the ''Huīxiān'' (灰仙 "Rat Immortal").

While the Fox God and the Weasel God always remain the two prominent members of the cult of the zoomorphic deities, the other positions vary in some regions including the Tiger, the Wolf, the Hare and the Turtle Gods.{{sfnb|Kang|2006|p=48}} Other areas host the worship of the Leopard, the Mole, the Toad and the Rabbit Gods.{{sfnb|Liu|2007}} In certain counties of [[Hebei]] they are reduced to four (四大仙 ''Sìdàxiān'') including the Fox, the Weasel, the Hedgehog and the Snake Gods.{{sfnb|Kang|2006|p=48}}

Common Chinese deities are associated to the cult of the zoomorphic gods. For instance, ''[[Huáng Dàxiān]]'' (黄大仙 "Great Yellow Immortal") is popular in north and northeast China, although he has no relation to [[Taoism]] as in southeastern China,{{sfnb|Wang|2013}} and is rather identified as the Weasel God.

Local terminology distinguishes the animal gods as the middle way between the ''shàngfáng shénxiān'' (上房神仙 "everlasting gods") gods of the greater [[cosmos]] important in Taoism, that are only worshipped and do not take possession of shamans; and the ''yīnxiān'' (陰仙 "underworld gods"), deceased beings who became gods through self-cultivation ([[ancestor]]s and [[progenitor]]s).{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=29}} In northeastern Taoism, besides the Fox Gods, the pantheon is headed by a goddess, the "Black Mother" (黑媽媽 ''Hēi māmā'').

===Shamanism===
Northeastern shamans consider themselves to be "disciples" (''dìzǐ'' 弟子) of the gods rather than mere channels of communication between the gods and the human world.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=2}} Another name used to refer to these ritual masters is ''xiāngtóu'' (香頭 "incense heads").{{sfnb|Li|2011}} Their practice is generally called ''chumaxian'' (出马仙), which means "the gods who take action" or more literally "riding for the immortals", a definition which implies that the gods and their disciples act as an organic whole, and in their action, form and content they express themselves together.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=3}}

There are two types of possession that the northeastern shamans experience in terms of consciousness: ''quánméng'' (全蒙 "complete unconsciousness", in which the disciple is not aware of what happens and what the god says) and ''bànméng'' (半蒙 "semi-unconsciousness", in which the disciple is aware of what happens during the possession).{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=32}}

They also practise a communication with ancestors through an [[ecstasy (emotion)|ecstatic]] experience called ''guòyīn'' (过阴 "passing to the underworld").{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=8}} This is part of the practices of both ''chumaxian'' and related communal rites of broader Chinese local religion.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=8}}

Northeastern [[Chinese shamanism]] shares similarities with southern Chinese mediumship (''[[tongji (spirit medium)|jitong]]''), Japanese [[Shinto]] practices, and various other shamanisms in the region ([[Tungusic peoples|Tungus]] and [[Manchu shamanism]], [[Mongolian shamanism]], [[Korean shamanism]], broader [[Siberian shamanism]]).{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=13}} Historically it is the result of the encounter of [[Han Chinese]] and [[Manchu people|Manchu]] cultures, especially the Han cult of the fox{{sfnb|Kang|2006}}{{sfnb|Huntington|2013}} and Manchu "wild ritual" (''wuwate'', Chinese: ''yějì'' 野祭).{{sfnb|Deng|2014|pp=13-18}}

Northeastern Chinese shamans are predominantly women, like the shamans of Northeast Asian shamanism, while southern Chinese mediums are almost exclusively men.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=13}} Moreover, while northeastern shamans are usually independent from formal religious institutions, southern medium specialists often collaborate with [[Taoist priest]]s.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=13}} Another distinction is that while southern mediums can acquire their role through training, and they are possessed mostly by Taoist and strictly Chinese gods, northeastern shamans are "chosen" or "ordained" by gods themselves (through ''mo'', "sickness"){{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=23}} as in other shamanic traditions, and their gods are animal totems.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=14}} When a future disciple is chosen, she experiences ''mo'' ("sickness").{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=23}}

===Places of worship and shaman halls===
In northeast China terminology for religious places and groups may follow the [[Chinese temple|common Chinese model]], with ''miao'' (庙) defining any "sacred precinct" dedicated to a god. However, a different terminology exists and temples may be called ''xiāntáng'' (仙堂 "hall of the immortals"){{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=2}} or ''tángzi'' (堂子), the latter name inherited from the temples of the ''bolongzi'' (Chinese: ''jiājì'' 家祭, "ancestral ritual") of Manchu shamanism.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=20}} Shamans also hold "immediate halls" of worship (''lìtáng'' 立堂) in their houses.{{sfnb|Deng|2014|p=27}}

===Folk religious sects===
[[File:Shanrendao.svg|thumb|100px|Coloured symbol of Shanrendao theory.]]
Since [[Chinese Buddhism]] and professional [[Taoism]] were never well developed in northeast China, the religious life of the region has been heavily influenced by networks of [[Chinese salvationist religions|folk salvationist sects]] and [[Confucian churches]], characterised by a congregational structure and a scriptural core.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=70}} During the Japanese occupation they weren't studied, but their role as a moral catalyser for the Han race was emphasised.{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=72}}

The [[Yiguandao]] (一貫道 "Consistent Way") had a strong presence in the area,{{sfnb|DuBois|2006|p=72}} but were especially the [[Guiyidao]] (皈依道 "Way of the Return to the One") and the [[Shanrendao]] (善人道 "Way of the Virtuous Man", which social body was known as the Universal Church of the Way and its Virtue) to have millions of followers in Manchuria alone.{{sfnb|Ownby|2008|ps=. § 23: "... the Daodehui eight million in Manchukuo alone (a quarter of the total population) in 1936-1937."}} Shanrendao remains widespread even after the Maoist period and the [[Cultural Revolution]], and headquarters of the Church of the Way and its Virtue have been re-established in [[Beijing]] in the 2010s. In more recent decades northeast China has also seen the rise of the [[Falun Gong]], which was founded in the 1990s in [[Jilin]].

During the period of ''Manchukuo'' also many [[Japanese new religions]], or independent [[Shinto sects and schools|Shinto sects]], proselytised in Manchuria establishing hundreds of congregations. Most of the missions belonged to the [[Omoto teaching]], the [[Tenri teaching]] and the [[Konko teaching]] of Shinto.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stalker|first=Nancy K.|year=2008|title=Prophet Motive: Deguchi Onisaburō, Oomoto, and the Rise of New Religions in Imperial Japan|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9IcxT_DsxN4C|isbn=0824832264|ref=harv}} p. 164.</ref> The Omoto teaching is the Japanese near equivalent of Guiyidao, as the two religions have common roots and history.

